def count_nonzero(df, keyword_list):
    keyword_list
    for i in np.arange(len(keyword_list)):
        BOOL = df.isin([keyword_list[i]])
        LENGTH = len(df.iloc[0])
        df_new = df.iloc[0:0]
        new_list = []
        for i in np.arange(LENGTH):
            df0 = BOOL.iloc[:,i].value_counts()
        newer = new_list.append(df0)
    data = pd.DataFrame(columns = selections_train, data = [newer], index = [keyword_list])
    data0 = df_new.append(data)
    return newer

def tokenize_df(df):
    empty = [] 
    four = []
    for i in range(len(df)):
        first = df.iloc[i][1]
        tokenized = tokenize(df, i)
        two = (tokenized)
        three = empty.append(two)
        aaa = (df.iloc[i][0])
        five = four.append(aaa)
    one = pd.DataFrame(data = empty, index = [four])
    return one

def convert(name):
    name = open(name).read()
    return (name)


def convert_list(list_name):
    listed = []
    for name in range(len(list_name)):
        name = [convert(list_name[name])]
        listed = np.append(listed, name)
    return(listed)

def tokenize(table, outlet_index):
    the_text = table.iloc[outlet_index][1]
    the_text = str(the_text)
    the_text.split
    the_text = ''.join([c for c in the_text if c not in punctuation]).lower().split()
    return the_text

def keyword_counts(df, pos_list, neg_list):
    leng = len(df.iloc[0:,:0])
    le = len(df.iloc[0])
    lists = []
    for i in np.arange(leng): 
        keys = ((le)-(df.iloc[i].isin(pos_list)).value_counts()[0])-((le)-(df.iloc[i].isin(neg_list)).value_counts()[0])
        lists = np.append(lists, keys)
    key = pd.DataFrame(index = selections_train, data = lists)
    return key

def word_count(list):
    stringing = str(list)
    counts = dict()
    words = stringing.split()
    for words in words:
        if words in counts:
            counts[words] += 1
        else:
            counts[words] = 1
    return counts

Defining a function to show us the movement of each dot

In [108]:
plt.close("all")
def make_arrow_plot(selections, x, y):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(30, 20))
    ax.scatter(x,y, c = colors, s = 3000)
    for i, txt in enumerate(selections):
        ax.annotate(txt, (x[i],y[i]), size = 40)
        for i in np.arange(10):
            plt.plot(x[i], y[i])
            plt.arrow(x[i], y[i], (x[i+10]-x[i]),
                      (y[i+10]-y[i]), linewidth = 10, 
                      length_includes_head = True, 
                      head_width = .1)

def keyword_counts_bipartisan(df, pos_list, neg_list):
    leng = len(df.iloc[0:,:0])
    le = len(df.iloc[0])
    lists = []
    for i in np.arange(leng): 
        keys = ((le)-(df.iloc[i].isin(pos_list)).value_counts()[0])-((le)-(df.iloc[i].isin(neg_list)).value_counts()[0])
        lists = np.append(lists, keys)
    key = pd.DataFrame(index = [df.index], data = lists)
    return key

WASHINGTON EXAMINER defense secretary jim mattis is misrepresenting the effectiveness of healthcare treatment for transgender people as a justification for a new policy that would bar many from serving in the military two leading associations of psychiatrists and psychologists say the pentagon’s claim that the scientific evidence is at best “unclear” for treatment of gender dysphoria the condition of being unhappy in your current gender and that treatment may not relieve serious risks such as suicide is not the current medical consensus according to the american psychiatric association and american psychological association “that’s really not true and it’s certainly not true among the actual experts who treat these people” said dr jack drescher a psychiatrist and psychoanalyst who is a distinguished fellow at the american psychiatric association “we shouldn’t assume just because somebody has a psychiatric diagnosis that they are not able to function and there is no reason to believe based on what we know of people who have gotten treatment for their gender dysphoria that they are any different policy bosses scott whitaker president and ceo of advamed watch full screen to skip ads if people get treatment for their gender dysphoria then they are doing fine” he said mattis announced plans last month to bar anyone diagnosed with gender dysphoria and anyone who has undergone treatment such as hormone therapy or surgery from enlisting in the military troops who are diagnosed while serving would be able to stay as long as they do not require treatment the secretary’s 44page review and recommendations use data from various outside research studies to make the case that people diagnosed with gender dysphoria suffer from high rates of suicide anxiety depression and substance abuse and that treatment such as hormone therapy and surgery have not been proven to relieve those issues “while there are numerous studies of varying quality showing that this treatment can improve health outcomes for individuals with gender dysphoria the available scientific evidence on the extent to which such treatments fully remedy all of the issues associated with gender dysphoria is unclear” mattis’ study concludes mattis also cited other key concerns in his rationale for rolling back the obama administration’s twoyearold policy of open service such as the amount of time gender dysphoria treatment can sideline troops and the difficulty of integrating transgender people into military units the proposed policy which remains on hold due to four federal lawsuits came after president trump declared last year that transgender troops would no longer be able to serve “in any capacity” because of costs of treatment and disruption mattis convened an expert pentagon panel to study the issue and spent three months crafting the new policy recommendations in his only public comment on the proposal mattis said the recommendations “stand on their own right
